  %h2 Why participate?
  %h3 For IETF'ers
  %p
    ACM SIGCOMM's
    %a{ :href => "http://www.sigcomm.org/events/imc-conference" } Internet Measurement Conference (IMC)
    is devoted to innovative and influential research in the area of network
    and Internet measurement. Topics range from Internet traffic analysis, to
    network management and security. Interest in Internet measurement has
    dramatically increased in recent years, reflecting the increasing
    understanding that measurement is critical to effective engineering of the
    Internet’s components. Over the years, IMC has become the premier conference
    in its field; it is now
    %em the
    conference for presenting and learning about all
    areas of Internet measurement.
  %p
    IETF’ers participating at RAIM will get a unique opportunity to hear about the
    latest results in Internet measurements and to exchange ideas with the top
    researchers in the field. Presenting industrial problems at RAIM will attract
    top academics to work on problems that are relevant to industry and help push
    forward the frontier of industrial knowledge.


  %h3 For IMC'ers
  %p
    The
    %a{ :href => "https://ietf.org/" } Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF)
    is a large open international
    community of network designers, operators, vendors, and researchers concerned
    with the evolution of the Internet architecture and the smooth operation of
    the Internet. It is open to any interested individual, and newcomers are
    encouraged to browse through
    %a{ :href => "https://www.ietf.org/tao.html" } The Tao of IETF
    and
    %a{ :href => "https://www.ietf.org/newcomers.html" } Getting Started in the IETF
    in order to learn a bit more about the organization. The IRTF, the Internet
    Research Task Force, is the IETF’s sister organization and promotes research
    of importance to the evolution of the Internet by creating focused, long-term
    research groups working on topics related to Internet protocols, applications,
    architecture and technology.
  %p
    IMC’ers participating at RAIM will be able to present their results to
    engineers working in key industrial positions. RAIM should help get your
    research ideas into practice. Moreover, the exchange with industry should help
    define new research problems.
  %p
    IMC'ers wishing to attend some of the IETF sessions in the week following the
    RAIM workshop are encouraged to contact the
    %a{ :href => "mailto:irtf-chair@irtf.org"} IRTF Chair
    to enquire about the availability of free or reduced IETF meeting registrations.


  %h2 Topics
  %p
    We encourage submission of position papers on all topics related to Internet
    measurements. Based on the submitted papers, the organizers will structure the
    workshop into themed sessions.
  %p
    Example topics of interest include:
  %ul
    %li performance measurements of broadband access networks
    %li measurement in an Internet with lots more ciphertext
    %li quantifying the extent of (or detecting) pervasive monitoring
    %li prevalence of impairments to end-to-end protocol transparency in the Internet
    %li overviews of the state-of-the-art in Internet measurements and remaining research challenges
    %li measurement-related industrial challenges and use cases
    %li measurements of the security and resilience of the global Internet infrastructure, including routing anomalies, prevalence of traffic with spoofed IP addresses, and resilience of the DNS
  %p
    Other interesting topics include those in the
    %a{ :href => "http://conferences2.sigcomm.org/imc/2015/cfp.html" } ACM IMC call-for-papers,
    especially when they relate to operational networks or applied techniques.



  %h2 Participation
  %p
    Workshop attendance is by invitation only. Individuals interested in
    participating are invited to submit
    %em one
    of the following two submission types at
    = succeed ":" do
      %a{ :href => "/raim-submit" } #{@config[:base_url]}/raim-submit
  %ol
    %li
      an original
      %em short position paper
      (four pages or less) outlining their views on topics related to the workshop; or
    %li
      a copy of a
      %em previously published academic paper
      related to the topics of the workshop.
  %p
    The collection of submitted position papers and references to published
    academic papers will be made available online. The IETF
    %a{ :href => "https://www.ietf.org/about/note-well.html" } “Note Well”
    does
    %em not
    apply to workshop submissions or any discussions at the workshop. We are
    investigating whether the workshop can be recorded and/or live-streamed.
    Remote inbound participation will not be possible.


